				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/a-random-day" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1841781); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1841781&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227504" alt="A Random Day" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1841781)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/a-random-day" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1841781); return false;" >A Random Day</a></span> <span class="odate time_1478730830 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Nov 2016 22:33</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2688307">
									

<p>I think it's fitting that after all this time, that after all this buildup to the Planet of the Hands and mankind's true home in the stars, we never got to see what it was like. We never left Earth. The Foundation tried to keep humanity shackled to the third planet from the sun, and as writers and readers for it, we rooted for the Foundation - we wanted to keep ourselves from reaching the stars.</p>
<p>I don't think I understand the time frame of the piece - is the piece being framed as a play for some reason? Is it actually a play occurring on the Planet of Hands, interspersed with vignettes occurring back on Earth? - but regardless, it's a worthy piece and definitely one of the most unique and artistically vivid 001s I've had the chance to read.</p>

							</div>

								
					
